>
  <p>
    Memoato is a low-friction memory for everyday life. You write what happened in your own words. The original note
    stays intact, while useful details become easier to find, connect, and understand later.
  </p>

  <blockquote class="editorial-quote">Do not track more. Remember the missing context.</blockquote>

  <h2>The gap between the apps</h2>
  <p>
    Trackers are excellent at objective activity. Calendars hold plans. Todo apps hold obligations. Email holds
    conversations, and notes hold long-form thinking. But real life happens between those systems.
  </p>
  <p>
    Why you skipped the gym. What hurt during a set. Which fallback kept the routine alive. How you felt before a big
    call. The tiny purchase detail you will need six months from now. That is Memoato territory.
  </p>

  <h2>Designed around people</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Natural capture</strong> — a sentence, a number, or an unfinished thought is enough.</li>
    <li><strong>Raw note first</strong> — your exact words are saved before anything is interpreted.</li>
    <li><strong>Helpful structure</strong> — facts and context become browsable without turning logging into a form.</li>
    <li><strong>Visible assumptions</strong> — suggestions can be confirmed, corrected, or ignored.</li>
    <li><strong>Forgiving by design</strong> — there are no streaks to break and no guilt for disappearing.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Quiet technology</h2>
  <p>
    Memoato uses automation where it removes friction, but the technology is not the product. The product is a calmer
    relationship with your own history: less effort while logging, more clarity when looking back.
  </p>
  <p>
    You can use the web app today, install it as a PWA, or connect tools such as Codex and Claude through the Memoato
    MCP. Privacy options include cloud sync, encrypted cloud, and local-only storage.
  </p>

  <h2>Built openly</h2>
  <p>
    Memoato is an open-source project from <a href="https://hills-lab.hr" rel="noopener noreferrer">HILLS Lab</a>,
    created by <a href="https://hrvoje.pavlinovic.com" rel="noopener noreferrer">Hrvoje Pavlinovic</a>. It is being
    built for real personal use first, with the ambition to become a useful memory layer for anyone whose life refuses
    to fit into neat boxes.
  </p>

